sentences: Chad Bromley (born March 8, 1979), better known by his stage name Apathy (formerly "The Alien Tongue"), is a rapper, producer and conspiracy theorist from Willimantic, Connecticut.
His first major release was his debut album; Eastern Philosophy in March 2006 with guest appearances from Celph Titled, Ryu, and Blue Raspberry.
His first major release was his debut album; Eastern Philosophy in March 2006 with guest appearances from Celph Titled, Ryu, and Blue Raspberry.
His second album Wanna Snuggle? was released in 2009 and his third studio album Honkey Kong was released in 2011, both to critical acclaim.
His second album Wanna Snuggle? was released in 2009 and his third studio album Honkey Kong was released in 2011, both to critical acclaim.
His fourth studio album, Connecticut Casual was released on June 3, 2014 and reached #41 in the R&B/Hip Hop Albums charts.
In 2001 Bromley joined Demigodz, a local rap collective that included Celph Titled, 7L & Esoteric, EL Fudge, Louis Logic and others.
In the period 2000 to 2002 he released a number of solo singles that included “Compatible”, “Just Begun”, “School”, and “Ain’t Nuttin’ Nice" released through Bronx Science Records.
Bromley made his album debut when he appeared on the Jedi Mind Tricks album The Psycho Social in 1997.
By mid-1997, the Demigodz collective fractured and Apathy together with producer Open Mic self-released the Sureshot Affair EP in 1998.
He continued to collaborate under the Demigodz moniker and released The Godz Must Be Crazy EP in 2002 on Ill Boogie Records.

After this second EP, Bromley signed on to Atlantic Records, but left the label in 2009 due to creative disagreements.
As a solo artist now, Bromley released the album, Eastern Philosophy, in March 2006 through Babygrande Records.

He was featured on their debut album; The Torture Papers released in 2006.
In January 2007, Apathy released another collection of his most recent works, Baptism by Fire.
In 2009, Get Busy Committee was formed in Los Angeles, California, by longtime friends Ryu (of Styles of Beyond), Apathy and Scoop DeVille.
Their debut album, Uzi Does It, was released for pre-sale download on October 27, 2009 at www.getbusycommittee.com, and available on iTunes and other outlets on November 10.
Their debut album, Uzi Does It, was released for pre-sale download on October 27, 2009 at www.getbusycommittee.com, and available on iTunes and other outlets on November 10.
As of 2012, Get Busy Committee is on hiatus, or "dead" as they refer to it; the group members are focused on their solo careers.
His third solo album, Honkey Kong was released on August 23, 2011 on Dirty Version Records, along with the Primate Mindstate EP as a bonus disk.
During 2011, Apathy and Celph Titled started producing a second duo album, called Will Sing for Vengeance.
In November 2011, Apathy uploaded on to YouTube a new song called "Demigodz Is Back", this song featured Apathy, Ryu and Celph Titled and was produced by Apathy.
On May 10, 2012, the pair also announced in an interview with Hiphopauthority.com that they were working on a new Demigodz album, titled Killmatic.
In 2012, Apathy released the double CD It's the Bootleg, Muthafuckas!
On January 14, 2013, Apathy confirmed that Killmatic would be released on March 5.
On January 14, 2013, Apathy confirmed that Killmatic would be released on March 5.
Four days later, Apathy, through his YouTube account, released the first single for Killmatic titled "Demigodz Is Back".
In July 2013, through his Twitter account, Apathy announced he was working on a new EP with Harry Fraud, titled Connecticut Casual.
It is due to be released April, 2014.
On November 30, 2013, Vinnie Paz revealed that two new Army Of The Pharaohs albums would be released in 2014.
On November 30, 2013, Vinnie Paz revealed that two new Army Of The Pharaohs albums would be released in 2014.
The first album; In Death Reborn is slated for a release on 22 April and the second LP is expected to drop in November.

On May 28, 2014, Apathy released "Martha Moxley (Rest in Peace)" featuring Chris Webby, Kappa Gamma, Annoyd and Hayze.
On June 30, 2015 Apathy released two projects: an EP called Weekend At The Cape and the fourth installment of his popular "It's the Bootleg, Muthafuckas!"

However, on February 17, 2016 he told on his Facebook page that it wasn't possible to release all three projects in 2016 and that The Widow's Son was delayed until early 2017.

On September 26, 2020, Apathy posted his planned releases for 2021 to his Instagram page.
On September 26, 2020, Apathy posted his planned releases for 2021 to his Instagram page.

On October 13, 2021, Apathy did an Instagram Live stream where he espoused a number of conspiracy theories, including the debunked theory that COVID-19 is a bioweapon, and condemned COVID-19 vaccine mandates (despite admitting that he himself reluctantly received the vaccine), believing them to be a part of the New World Order, and also condemned cancel culture, describing it as "horrifying" and comparing it to "witch hunts."
